SIMPLE: flit
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Flit
<hw>Flit</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Flitted</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Flitting</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>flitten</ets>, <ets>flutten</ets>, to carry away; cf. Icel.
<ets>flytja</ets>, Sw. <ets>flytta</ets>, Dan. <ets>flytte</ets>.
⟦root⟧84. Cf. <er>Fleet</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To move with celerity through the air; to fly away with a rapid
motion; to dart along; to fleet; <as>as, a bird <ex>flits</ex> away; a
cloud <ex>flits</ex> along.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A shadow <qex>flits</qex> before me.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To flutter; to rove on the wing.</def>
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To pass rapidly, as a light substance, from one
place to another; to remove; to migrate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It became a received opinion, that the souls of men, departing
this life, did <qex>flit</qex> out of one body into some other.</q>
<rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To remove from one place or habitation to
another.</def> <mark>[Scot. & Prov. Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Wright.
Jamieson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To be unstable; to be easily or often
moved.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And the free soul to <qex>flitting</qex> air resigned.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flit</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Flit
<hw>Flit</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Nimble; quick; swift.
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> See <er>Fleet</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flitch</ent>⟦br⟧
